title: Delta Printer Filament holder Mk2 100% poly

description.text:
This filament holder is basically a thrust bearing, and after some thought I released that whilst printing ball bearings is unlikely to yield good results, it is possible to print a tapered roller bearing.

So, my Mk2 design does that, gone are the steel balls of my original concept and are replaced by tapered rollers.

This design also includes retainer clips so the races can be moved without all the bearings falling out.

Again this race can have multiple uses, and this version can even be used vertically, but it wont have the same load bearing capacity of the steel ball version. however the load bearing capacity can be increased by using more rollers

All parts on my build are printer with 0.2mm layer height.

The basic build requires 12 rollers, when printing these make sure you plate them end on with the largest end in the plate, there is chamfer at this end but its there to try and reduce flash from the bed.

Its possible to build this without the spacer, by filling the race with rollers, this will increase the load bearing properties, but you probably better make sure yur rollers print very well.

All parts can be printed without support

Before assembling the race make sure the rollers can move through the race smoothly and they are free in the spacer, take your time and adjust with an exacto knife if necessary.

description.text:
The REPY-2.0 is an open source mechanical module for researching Modular Robotics. It is designed to be printed on a Low-cost 3D printer, like a RepRap. The main points taken into account when designed were:
  • Symmetry. This way, the robot can move whatever the orientation of the module is.
  • Low-cost. Modular robotics is usually a expensive area of research due to the fact that many small independent robots (modules) have to be built in order to build the main robot. Having a 3D printable design enables us to lower the cost of each module.
  • Customization. With the same code it can be able to generate different modules according to the electronics and motors chosen. If our motor or board is not yet implemented we can do it easily by using the existent modules as examples, and with our new module the program will be able to generate a custom REPY-2.0 module.
    • You can find more information about REPY-2.0 on:
  • d-squared:wiki - REPY-2.0
    • And the source code and updated stl files on:
  • REPY-2.0 - github.com
    • This work is based on REPY module, by Juan Gonzalez-Gomez (Obijuan):
  • Juan Gonzalez-Gomez (Obijuan) on Thingiverse
  • Juan Gonzalez-Gomez (Obijuan) on Github
    • More information about Juan Gonzalez-Gomez's work on
  • Thingiverse - REPY v1.1
  • [iearobotics - REPY v1.1 (Spanish)]( http://www.iearobotics.com/wiki/index.php?title=M%C3%B3dulos_REPY-1)

Choose the file accordingly to the servo and horn to be used. Not all of them have been printed and tested. At this moment only the following ones are validated:
  • REPY-2.0 for Fake Futaba 3003s servo: lower part and rounded, 4-arms and 6-arms horns.
  • REPY-2.0 for Tower Pro sg90 servo: lower part and 2-arms horn.
    • If you print one that is not in the list of validated ones, please let me know if it works or not, to fix the file or add it to the list. Detailed assembly instructions on: d-Squared:robotics wiki

description.text:
Need an end cap for your new CNC Mill, 3D Printer, or Lasersaurus T-Slot aluminum extrusion? With or without holes? Single or double wide?

Look no more - why buy when you can print! This OpenSCAD model lets you create an end cap by making a few measurements or looking into the extrusion data sheets.

Warning: You may need to repair the generated STL files with netfabb. Trying to work out why OpenSCAD is generating a non-manifold object. If you can work out why please comment.

You can easily set: 

  * Generate single (N x N) or double (N x 2N) end cap  
  * End cap thickness  
  * Number of holes  
  * Size of hole(s)  
  * Length of tabs that fit into the T-slots

If you've got the extrusion data sheets then your in luck as most of the dimensions will be already to hand. Otherwise measure:

  • Base of T Slot: 

      - gap width at base of T  
  - extrusion thickness at base of T

  • T Crossbar: 

     - void length of crossbar  
 - void thickness of crossbar

  • Top of Crossbar:

    Most extrusion tapers at the top of each T slot void, this is modeled with a trapezoid joined to the top of the crossbar 

     - length at bottom of trapezoid (normally the same at the crossbar length)  
 - length at top of trapezoid  
 - width of trapezoid

The OpenSCAD is configured for a Felix Printer to generate an end cap for a JANSJÖ IKEA LED lamp modification as shown. But don't let that limit you, download and modify as needed. All parameters are fully documented in the code.

HOW TO: Model a spring

One quick method (of many and maybe not the best) for designing and printing custom compression springs.

There are lots of methods for making springs and as many different CAD packages.

Having said that, the basic principles are often very similar.

So, don't panic if this demo uses one CAD program and your using another. What's important is the basic steps.

Remember that you can resize and scale the spring model at any time. Changing the diameter of the starting cylinder will also give you different properties for the spring. 

 Here's a great link to the Khan academy lesson on spring physics.  

 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZzwuHS9ldbY  

 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eVl5zs6Lqy0

BASIC STEPS TO MODEL A SPRING:

  1. Create a cylinder or use a cylinder "primitive"
  2. Extrude or sweep one end surface
  3. Angle (Twist and turn) that surface
  4. Extruding additional angled levels.

See steps in sequential images (above).

Here are two sets of x,y,z angles that demonstrate the process.

  1. 20,20,10
  2. 10,10,5
  • Negative angles will reverse the direction of the coil.

Play around with these numbers and have fun.

Hope this is useful!

description.text:
This is the beta version of my 1,75mm bowden extruder. I have managed to print Ninjaflex material @ 30mm/s with a bowden length of about 0,5m in a horizontal setup using an E3Dv6 - 0.3mm hotend. See the instructions site for hints on printing TPE.

General:

  • The mainbody is designed to fit a MK8 drive gear from reprap.me. I have not tested it with any other drive gear or with any other setup.
  • Mounting holes: 4,5mm (spacing: 60mm)
  • Please keep in mind that this is still a beta version.

IMPORTANT:

  • You need a metal, drilled through, 1/8 BSP pushfit. Otherwise it will not work. There is a version for the e3d plastic push fits planed and i will upload it as soon as possible.
  • The mainbody is designed to fit the reprap.me MK8 drive gear with an effective diameter of 6,7mm. There are a lot of MK8 drive gears out there that are claimed to have 7mm. I do not know if and how good they work.
  • The nominal diameter for the pushfit bore is 9,2mm and for the MR105 bearing i used 10,1mm. If you run into trouble with cracking the body or something else, please let me know.

Known / possible issues:

  • Overtightening:
    Do not overtighten the lever or you will flatten the filament and it will get stuck.
  • On filament change, sometimes there is a little drip of extra filament from the hot end that is carried back through the ptfe tube to the extruder. This may cause some problems in pulling the filament out of the extruder. In version 3.1 i have changed the roundings and chamfers a little bit to avoid this. But it needs further testing.

Material list:
1x printed parts
1x Nema17 stepper
1x MK8 drive gear
1x 1/8 BSP metal push fit - drilled through!!!!
5x M3x30 screws DIN912
1x M3x5 screw DIN912
7x M3 washers
2x M3 nuts
2x springs (8mm length works well)
1x 635ZZ bearing (19/5/6)
1x MR105ZZ bearing (10/5/4)
1x Piece of 5mm rod, length: 15mm

additional parts for easier assembly:
2x pieces 4mm ptfe tube
1x piece of filament

Assembly:
1) Print the parts. I suggest you to use the supported version of the main body.
2) Clean the parts from the support material, and drill the holes using the drill pattern.
3) Clip the bearing into the lever using the 5mm rod.
4) Push the drive gear onto the stepper motor. Do not tighten it yet.
5) This is the hardest part. Screw the push fit carefully into the main Body. Pay attention to keep it aligned.
6) Mount the MR105 bearing.
7) Mount the main body and the lever onto the stepper.
8) Mount the screws and springs for the lever.
9) Push the ptfe tubes into the push fit and the main body
10) Push a piece of filament through the extruder. Now you can adjust and tighten the drive gear easily.

Ninjaflex:

  • The most important thing is the right spring load. It has to be realy low. If you feel it is way too low, it's normaly the right load. ;)
  • I am using a temperature of about 225°C to 235°C.
  • Printing speed should be between 15mm/s and 30mm/s.
  • I am using a flow multiplier of 1.1
  • 4mm and 20mm/s is a good starting point for the retraction settings

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/gdF7bRLqiXi
Made in TinkerCAD

This one derived from the original maker, I only made more improvement to this especially the structure. This design would have your m3 bolts flushed in the surface and creates seamless anti backlash/wobble z axis thingamajig

The idea here is to accommodate as thin anti wobble/backlash z axis carriage depending on your screw length.

Update 5 september 2015
I adjusted the gap between flange nut mount and hole for smooth rod shorter because having them tight fit might make the wobble still there because when there's a backlash, the threaded rod will push itself to the smooth rod and thus the wobble still there (theoretically)

There are 2 main parameters;

total length - This is the total threaded screw length (head not included)
minus - Basically you don't have to adjust this, but this is the thickness of the brass flange nut thread length for screw. Setting this to 0 will have the screw unable to reach the flange

The provided stl is for M3 x 6mm bolt

the thickness calculated in this script is;

total thickness = (total length - minus)+2mm (for housing the bolt's head)

comments.text: I don't want to be a Debbie Downer but I kind feel like I must if you are asking. The MPCNC is a good machine at the price it simply cannot be beat. You will learn a lot and in that way it's worth it so you can see if it's a hobby you actually enjoy. That said I wouldn't recommend it. You will spend more time trying to get the machine to work then you will using it for productive things. First of all because of it's kinda flimsy construction you will need to cut slow, much slower than you would with a real cnc. 2nd while you can dial it it in, it's very hard to make a perfectly square cut. This isn't too much of an issue on smaller pieces or things like signs or decorations, but when you are milling a case for a 3D Printer having a case that's even slightly out of square will wreck havoc on your print quality.The printer I built using this case is being taken apart right now because the case just wasn't square enough to get good results. I still enjoyed my time with the machine but i was happy to see it go. To counter my argument though I bought a 6040 CNC frame and wired everything else up myself at a cost of about $900, a little more than double what i spent on building the MPCNC so each person has to make up there own mind but I would say when it comes to CNCs i wouldn't go lower price/quality than an X-Carve. Buying something that works the first time will end up saving you time and money if you stick with the hobby.

This part goes with my other part (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:985629) to make the y-axis much more rigid and easier adjustment for belt tension.
This does require you to drill 3 holes in the frame, so do at your own risk. Measure twice, drill once!

I printed this in abs, as it what I normally print with but I assume PLA etc should be fine.
Some of the holes may need a slight Dremel/drill here and there as hardware isn't the same everywhere.

1) For the most strength I recommend printing the parts as if they were going on your printer(as is top is top, bottom is bottom etc)

2) I used some hardware laying around for the bolt, which in my case was a M5x40mm hex bolt with a wingnut

3) Re-use the stock bearings etc, but for the tensioning bolt, I had to squeeze it in place by tightening the wingnut down and forcing the bolt into the plastic. Should be fine if using a m5 hex bolt.

4) The mounting holes are 40mm apart, I drilled mine bigger to allow fine tuning the idler. Do the same for the hex bolt.

title: D3D (Dglass 3D) hotend fan shroud
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Edit: uploaded a v4 of the fan shroud design - it's probably not printable on an FDM printer (maybe it is, with soluble support) while keeping it structurally safe. Works okay on SLA printers, though.

The original (kickstarter era) D3D auto-lift hotend fan shroud was prone to breaking and got replaced by a new design by the hotend authors.

However, both suffer from the same issue the early E3D fan shrouds were suffering from - they're printed oriented wrong, so they tend to loosen up and delaminate after a while or even when getting it onto the hotend heat sink.

I've designed my own, more similar to the first D3D design than the second one, but meant to be printed oriented 90 degrees rotated, so the layers don't separate under the stress of the heat sink clamp. There are other tiny tweaks all over the place.

It mounts easily, clamps well (no rattle or vibration) and the fan screw holes should work without tapping.

Original version:

Print without support (assuming you have at least basic bridging dialed in on your pinter - the bridges are very very short).

Give it enough "meat" - 30-50% infill - so there's enough strength to clamp on the heatsink and enough material for the screws to bite into.

To mount on a hotend, slide it from the top of the hotend onto the heatsink, then wiggle a little until you get it all the way down to the last fin. The shroud should go over the last (larger) fin - there's a small inset in the bottom of the clamp that allows this to happen.

DO NOT force ONTO the heatsink from the side / front. I repeat - SLIDE OVER the heatsink from the top (from the cold end side).

Tested on D3D auto-lift hotends (http://www.dglass3d.com/products/autolift-hot-ends/), might work on regular D3D hotends as well (can't test, don't have them).

Version 4 UPDATE: uploaded a v4 of the fan shroud design - it's probably not printable on an FDM printer (maybe it is, with soluble support) while keeping it structurally safe. Works okay on SLA printers, though.

title: The Dowelinator - for IKEA Omar shelves

description.text: Once again, IKEA comes to the rescue! With this thing you can fix ~22mm dowels (or a broom stick, if you're in a pinch) in almost any length to your Omar and subsequently stick your spools on there!

Print in your favourite material, with your favourite settings. The load path is pretty straight forward, so I'd consider anything above 15% infill and 1.6mm walls overkill. My PLA-PHA specimens held up fine for more than four months in roasty-toasty summer temperatures.

The dowel can be slightly under-/oversized, 20mm up to 25mm should also work fine. The stuff I picked up at the local hardware store was 22mm, so that's what's going into the description! :D

As a small note:
I personally keep my spools in 3L-Toppits zip bags, what for keeping the dust away but also for moisture control, with a small baggy of silica gel packed with each spool.

description.text:
I moved to a new place on my own, and needed a simple, painfree and good-looking handle so I could transport my printer easily on public transport.

I came up with this design, which utilizes four of the mounting holes in the top of the frame (easily drilled if needed) and it houses small Ø8mm super strong magnets to hold small tools!

You need to print the handle twice so you can sandwich them on the 3-4mm frame.
I used m3 bolts and nuts because that is the size of the holes in my frame, but the holes in the handle are m4.

Pro tip: use some soft material sticker on the handle to make transporting your printer even more comfortable!
Microsoft MCT

title: ***NOW WITH TBS CORE SUPPORT*** TBS Discovery (Team BlackSheep) Brushless Gimbal / upgrade to Discovery Pro

description.text:
As requested, here I present my brand new design of the gimbal.

Now you can use it along with the TBS Core, as the backside dampening was moved to the top making space free at the bottom.

If you don't use the Core, then keep in mind that this dampening method based on compression, might be slightly better than the prevois one... So you might as well try this new one out :)
